post_text:
Hold on to your hats! This week is going to be fast and furious.

First of all, it's Homecoming Week! Don't forget to participate in Spirit Week - there may be slight variations in different buildings. We can't wait to see our students showing their support as we Bash the Bluejays! Add our Homecoming Frame to your profile picture or the pictures you take with your Facebook camera!

Second, activities are really taking off. If you haven't received an Orange Calendar yet, let your office know so that you can stay in the know - check your student's backpack first, though. They should have come home with the youngest student by Friday!

Most of all, we are excited to continue our Fall Sports and the Homecoming Festivities we have planned. We know you might be missing our traditional Homecoming Dance. Don't worry - StuCo membership is planning and organizing an alternative event in the future to replace the homecoming dance this year. In the meantime, help us make this another memorable year for our Eagles! #WeAreTheEagles315 #bashthebluejayshoco2020

This week our CHS football team heads to Hugoton for a Battle of the ü¶Ö. Next week, CHS will be hosting the Cimarron Bluejays for our 2020 Homecoming. As you might understand, this year doesn't include all of our traditional homecoming festivities. We are excited to still be having üèÉ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è üèà üèêFall Sports and Activities üéæ ‚õ≥ üé∫as well as the üéâ Spirit and Fun üéä that CHS Homecoming brings.

Our CHS StuCo Sponsors have focused on what we can do safely and we fully support that plan. Every year, the Philanthropic Education Organization reviews essays submitted by our Colby Public Schools' students and chooses a deserving teacher among the nominees to be the Most Inspirational Teacher of the Year. The trophy then resides in the office of that teacher for all to see.

This year, Mrs. Krysti Terrell, a 2nd Grade Teacher at CGS, was nominated by Brielle Bange and chosen by the PEO. Brielle wrote an essay explaining Mrs. Terrell's influence on her as a student and person.

Congratulations, Mrs. Terrell! CGS is honored to have the trophy housed in their Primary Building Office. CPS is proud of the inspiration you have been and continue to be to our students!

post_text:
This week Colby Public Schools will host scrimmages at home for our students, parents, and community members as we kick off our Fall Sports/Activities Seasons. We want to let our student-athletes play, but we are trying our best to keep both them and the community that wants to watch them healthy and safe.

To do that, we will be observing some different game-day operations. We know that not everyone will appreciate or agree with the choices that we feel we need to make. We are asking you to take a minute and think things through before becoming frustrated or annoyed.

We ask our student-athletes to trust the process. We encourage them to buy into the program that their coaches present even if (sometimes especially if) they cannot see the benefit. We are asking you to do the same. Just like with a penalty or referee call during the game, please take the new procedures in stride and know that in the end, students in school and athletes on the field and court are our end goals. Thank you.
#WeAreTheEagles315 #ReadyToLearn315

The preschool will be funded through three grants: the Kansas Preschool Pilot Grant, the Kansas 4-Year Old At-Risk Grant, and the Greater Northwest Kansas Community Foundation Grant.

Applications are available by calling:
BEFORE July 1st - (785) 672-3125 ext. 161
AFTER July 1st - (785) 460-6067

post_text:
Mr. Ross is retiring after 29 years with Colby Public Schools! Yeah, he came here clear back in 1991! That‚Äôs like FOREVER ago! For crying out loud, a postage stamp only cost 25¬¢ way back then. So here‚Äôs what we are going to do to wish him well!

We are having a ‚ÄúDrive By and Wave Goodbye‚Äù on Friday, June 19 from 11:30 am ‚Äì 12:30 pm during the lunch pick up. Swing by CMS during that time and as you drive by, give Mr. Ross a big wave! You don‚Äôt have to be picking up a lunch, come on by anyway. A lot of us should probably stop and thank him for putting up with us for all those years, but a hearty wave goodbye will work better.

Help us share and get the word out. We want to see you all there on Friday! #WeAreTheEagles315

Do you remember learning to blow bubbles? It's a frustrating process until the one time it just works! So, here's our thought for Motivational Monday - find that one thing that you haven't been able to master and try it one more time. It just might be the one time it works!

This 1st Grader was in Mrs. Schnider's class last year! As a grade level, they enjoyed a "50s in First Grade Day" wearing clothes from the 1950s and learning with era style work and fun! We walked through just as they were teaching each other the art of blowing some BIG bubbles with bubble gum.

#WeAreTheEagles315 #MotivationalMondaysAt315

ü•≥Congratulations to Adriana Mendezüëè for receiving a Kansas Seal of Biliteracy at the Intermediate Silver Level!

What does this mean?
"The Kansas Seal of Biliteracy is awarded by the Kansas State Department of Education (KSDE) and Colby Public Schools to recognize each student who has attained proficiency in English and one or more other world languages by the time of graduation.

It is a statement of accomplishment that recognizes a student‚Äôs readiness for career and college, and for engagement as a global citizen."
- KSDE Seal of Biliteracy Advisory Council

üß°üñ§ü¶ÖCHSü¶Öüñ§üß° is so proud of you, Adriana, and can't wait to see you start the next steps of your journey! #WeAreTheEagles315 #CHSEaglePRIDE315 #WeAre315 #ColbyEagles #cpseaglepride

post_text:
Happy National Teacher Appreciation Week! Now, more than ever, we have cause to be proud to be an educator, grateful to have such wonderful colleagues, and be a part of the Colby Public Schools family.

The past couple of months have been hard. We have had to transition from your classroom to remote learning, setting up new lesson plans, preparing materials, and finding new ways to check in on and connect with our students. And all of us have done this while juggling the effects of COVID-19 on our family and personal lives as well.

I‚Äôm proud of our efforts and Colby Public Schools will continue to work hard to support you as you continue to support the children and families in our community. I know that we will take everything we have learned through this experience to make the educational opportunity for children in Colby even better when we are able to return to our buildings. Have a wonderful week.

Sincerely,
Katina Brenn
Superintendent
#WeAreTheEagles315
#CPSEaglePRIDE

post_text:
It's time again to look at enrollment for our next Kindergarten class! We know that this may be your first time with us and we are excited to have you join us!

Any child residing in the Colby Public School District (USD 315) who will be five years old on or before August 31, 2020, is eligible to enroll. The final enrollment will be in August. At that time, we will need copies of your child's immunization records, birth certificate, and social security card.

To get started, we will need some basic information so that we can get your child(ren) into our system. Please proceed to Kindergarten Pre-Enrollment for 2020-2021. https://bit.ly/2yzLFW8

Thank you, and welcome to Colby Public Schools!

#CGSEaglePRIDE

post_text:
It's time again to look at enrollment for our next Kindergarten class! We know that this may be your first time with us and we are excited to have you join us!

Any child residing in the Colby Public School District (USD 315) who will be five years old on or before August 31, 2020, is eligible to enroll. The final enrollment will be in August. At that time, we will need copies of your child's immunization records, birth certificate, and social security card.

To get started, we will need some basic information so that we can get your child(ren) into our system. Please proceed to Kindergarten Pre-Enrollment for 2020-2021. https://bit.ly/2yzLFW8

Thank you, and welcome to Colby Public Schools!

#CGSEaglePRIDE

post_text:
We are aware that Odysseyware is currently giving an error that we have exceeded our license count and will not let you access the system. We have been in contact with the company and were informed that due to the immense number of licenses that went active as of today (CPS has 10,000 licenses alone), the Odysseyware systems are trying to process the massive increase in licensing and it is taking time to do so.

There are no issues with equipment at this time, it is simply a matter of getting an immense number of licenses processed in a short period of time. Unfortunately, Odysseyware could not give us an estimate of when this license upgrade would be done so we are as much at the mercy of this issue as you.

As soon as we have more information, we will let you know.

Thank you,

CPS Administration

Colby Public Schools' teachers and staff met today to plan for Continued Learning in our district. It looked a little different as we took advantage of some of the technology that our students will use in order to maintain CDC standards of a safe distance.

Teachers are calling families today and tomorrow as they check in on their students, discuss the resources available at home, and discuss concerns our parents might have. We are learning about the new state guidelines and exploring options available within the curriculum we are already using. Please use this time to get contact information - your student's teacher will be your best contact!

One thing is for certain - our teachers love our kids! They are working hard to find the best in this situation and continue to make a positive impact on kids and our community!

#CPSEaglePRIDE #CPSEaglesAtHome

post_text:
We know that we as adults are full of questions, but what about our kids? How can we best talk about all of the big changes with them?

10 Tips for Talking about COVID-19 with Kids:
1. Make children feel safe.
2. Give them facts and let them lead the discussion.
3. Give them power - and responsibility.
4. Let them know what to expect.
5. Receive their emotions with empathy.
6. Keep your child's developmental stage and temperament in mind.
7. Try to maintain a normal routine.
8. Model the behavior you want to see.
9. Consider adjusting the screen time limits.
10. Take care of yourself.

For more in-depth information, find an extended version of these tips at https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/10-tips-for-talking-about-covid-19-with-your-kids

Parents and students,

Good afternoon, by now many of you have heard of Governor Kelly's announcement earlier today regarding the remainder of this school term. Over the next several days and weeks, we will be providing information to you either as it becomes available to us or as decisions are made locally.

Please be patient as we work through this and bear in mind that we have never found ourselves in this situation and so we do not have a precedent from which to operate. Many decisions and changes must be made and implemented in a very short time. We will be doing our very best to make this transition as smooth as possible.

To this end, a "button" has been placed on all the district websites (district, grade school, middle school, and high school sites) with the label "Coronavirus Information". It is placed in the top, right corner of all sites so you can access all the information from any of your current bookmarks.

We have placed important information on this page for you and ask that you access it at your earliest convenience.



Colby Public Schools Administration

Per KSHSAA instructions:
Effective Monday, March 16, all spring sports and activities are suspended through Sunday, March 22. This includes the cancellation of all practices and competitions for this week. This prohibition is consistent with KSDE and governmental guidance and may be extended, should conditions warrant. Please note spring sports team members are prohibited from club or outside team participation and practice during this period. Not only would such outside participation be contrary to handbook rule, but it would also be contrary to the very reason activities are canceled during the time we seek to mitigate the potential transfer of the contagion.

Thank you for your cooperation.

post_text:
Congratulations to April, the MARCH 2020 STUDENT OF THE MONTH for Colby Rotary.

Some of April's special honors and activities include: Superintendent's Honor Roll; National Honor Society; Forensics - 3 years State Qualifier; School Musicals and Plays; Cosmic Crayon; Student Environment Club; Tennis; Track; Band; and Piano. She has also participated in 4-H for 7 years completing multiple service and club projects, plus serving as Vice President of her club and Dog Club President. For many summers, April has operated a Lemonade Stand to raise funds for a local animal shelter where she was made an honorary board member.

April's future plans include attending Sterling College to pursue a degree in psychology.
